00:10:44.599 --> 00:10:51.559
we basically double down on the JSON approach. So the search module exports a variable,

00:10:51.559 --> 00:10:57.799
which is defined in the JSON. So it has an exports field. And the graph module then imports

00:10:57.799 --> 00:11:03.880
a certain variable. In this case, it imports the org ID variable. And that is mapped to the selected

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:11.559
ID variable of the other module using a path. You see it finds the selected ID on page one,

00:11:11.559 --> 00:11:21.159
tile one in the search module. So on the R side, it will look like this. If you recall,

00:11:21.159 --> 00:11:27.719
every module has a UI and a server function. And because it is a function, it has inputs and

00:11:27.719 --> 00:11:33.719
outputs, which we can use to inject basically the information that we need to get this working.

00:11:34.679 --> 00:11:39.719
So if we start by the outputs, that's a bit easier. So if in your R code for the search

00:11:40.359 --> 00:11:47.000
function, you return basically the ID that a user selects, then another module can import that

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:54.760
via the inputs and make it work. Why does it work? Well, these two are reactive values,

00:11:55.960 --> 00:12:01.159
which helps a lot because reactive values are under the hood, like R6 objects, and they are

00:12:01.159 --> 00:12:06.760
